=3D"content_GYj0UnA9 TM_dkKeNHYB normalWeight_dkKeNHYB">You=E2=80=99re work=
ing on a paper, and you=E2=80=99ve just written a line that seems kind of f=
amiliar. Did you read it somewhere while you were researching the topic? If=
 you did, does that count as plagiarism? Now that you=E2=80=99re looking at=
 it, there are a couple of other lines you borrowed from somewhere. You did=
n=E2=80=99t bother with a citation when writing because you didn=E2=80=99t =
plan to keep those lines. But now they=E2=80=99re an important part of your=
 paper. Is it still plagiarism if they make up less than a paragraph?<br><b=
r>

Using someone else=E2=80=99s text without attribution is plagiarism, whethe=
r you mean to do it or not. In fact, a writer can even commit plagiarism by=
 using their own work without proper citation. <br><br>

Unintentional plagiarism of even a sentence or two can have serious consequ=
ences. For students, plagiarism often means a failing grade, academic proba=
tion, or worse.  Fortunately, it=E2=80=99s easy to ensure the authenticity =
of your work by using a plagiarism checker. Doing so will help you spot any=
 unintentional use of others' words or ideas and prevent academic consequen=
ces in the future. <br></div></details><details class=3D"container_GYj0UnA9=
"><summary class=3D"button_GYj0UnA9"><h3 class=3D"TM_dkKeNHYB normalWeight_=
dkKeNHYB">What are the different types of plagiarism?</h3><span class=3D"ar=
rowContainer_GYj0UnA9" aria-hidden=3D"true"><svg width=3D"12" height=3D"7" =
viewBox=3D"0 0 12 7" fill=3D"none" xmlns=3D"http://www.w3.org/2000/svg"><pa=
th d=3D"M0.5 0.5L6 6L11.5 0.5" stroke=3D"currentColor" stroke-linecap=3D"ro=
und"></path></svg></span></summary><div class=3D"content_GYj0UnA9 TM_dkKeNH=
YB normalWeight_dkKeNHYB">You might be surprised to learn there are eight t=
ypes of plagiarism:<br><br>

1. Complete plagiarism is an overt form of plagiarism. This happens when yo=
u present someone else=E2=80=99s work as your own, such as buying an essay =
or using another=E2=80=99s work without credit.<br><br>

2. Direct plagiarism is copying sections of another=E2=80=99s work without =
crediting the author rather than copying the entire piece like complete pla=
giarism.<br><br>

3. Paraphrasing plagiarism is rewording someone else's work without credit.=
 Even if the ideas aren=E2=80=99t in the original words, this form of <a re=
l=3D"noopener noreferrer" class=3D"link-color_linkDefault__xgSfW link-color=
_styles2024__s1yEi" target=3D"_blank" href=3D"https://www.grammarly.com/par=
aphrasing-tool"><u>paraphrasing</u></a> is still plagiarism.<br><br>

4. Self-plagiarism is reusing your own previous work in a new context. Even=
 if it=E2=80=99s your original thought, this can be considered plagiarism.<=
br><br>

5. Patchwork plagiarism, also known as mosaic plagiarism, involves integrat=
ing plagiarized material with your own work, often subtly.<br><br>

6. Source-based plagiarism consists of <a rel=3D"noopener noreferrer" class=
=3D"link-color_linkDefault__xgSfW link-color_styles2024__s1yEi" target=3D"_=
blank" href=3D"https://www.grammarly.com/citations"><u>citing sources</u></=
a> in a misleading way. For instance, a writer may refer to a secondary sou=
rce in their work but only cite the primary source from which the secondary=
 source was taken. This form of plagiarism can also include making up sourc=
es or citing incorrect sources.<br>
<br>
7. Accidental plagiarism, as the name suggests, happens when the author pla=
giarizes content unintentionally. It can include failing to cite sources, n=
ot putting quotes around cited material, and making mistakes when citing so=
urces. Despite being accidental, this type of plagiarism still carries seri=
ous consequences. <br><br>8. AI plagiarism is using writing created with <a=
 rel=3D"noopener noreferrer" class=3D"link-color_linkDefault__xgSfW link-co=
lor_styles2024__s1yEi" target=3D"_blank" href=3D"https://www.grammarly.com/=
ai/generative-ai"><u>generative AI</u></a> without disclosing its origin. W=
hen you use gen AI to write, summarize, or paraphrase, you need to include =
a citation.<br></div></details><details class=3D"container_GYj0UnA9"><summa=
ry class=3D"button_GYj0UnA9"><h3 class=3D"TM_dkKeNHYB normalWeight_dkKeNHYB=
